 I can only hope that a few words and my 37 hours of play-time may convince you to give yourself the opportunity to experience what this game has to offer. Even if you end up hating it, I'd rather you gave it a shot than miss a work of art. That doesn't do it justice. Team Cherry painted their Mona Lisa on the first canvas. I can't overstate enough how profound this game was for me.\n\nPros:\n\n- The controls are tight and responsive. When you press buttons, the character reacts. The protagonist isn't floaty and input is responsive.\n\n- The art is gorgeous. Every single asset is hand drawn and animated, reminiscent of Skull Girls. Even if you don't like the art you have to appreciate the skill and beauty of what was done here.\n\n- The soundtrack is appropriately melancholy as you explore the derelict depths of Hollownest. The boss music is intense and adds character where it should. \n\n- The story, while vague, is presented wonderfully as I've stated above. You will be left with questions at the end of the game, but they are intended. What better excuse to explore the world more and decipher answers?\n\n- The progression is solid. You collect abilities and powers via metroidvania exploration, and you buy upgrades and other abilities via a souls-like currency system.\n\n- The difficulty can be challenging. I like to believe, for the majority of the game, not overwhelmingly so. It seems enough so that I always feel like my mechanics are being pushed. This is something I hope anyone playing metroidvania or souls-likes is looking for.\n\nCons:\n\n- Due to the game's cryptic and vague nature, figuring out what to do and how to do it can be challenging at times. Beyond what may be desirable. It may get to the point that you find yourself looking something up online or backtracking unnecessarily. I'm listing it as a soft-con.\n\n- Out of the two faults I have with this game, this one would be the dealbreaker for some people. There is a STEEP difficulty spike towards the end of the game. Some of the bosses will make you want to rip your hair out, but even those are a common staple of souls-likes and pale in comparison to my main qualm. There is a REQUIRED platforming section nearing the game's conclusion that unlocks the path for the \"true\" endings. This platforming section is of the lowest circles of hell. Super Meat Boy is the only comparison I can give. Be prepared for that torture when the time comes. If it wasn't that bad, I wouldn't put it in a review.\n\nPRO TIP (NO REAL SPOILERS): There are ONLY 3 endings. 1 you get from following the standard path, and the other 2 hinge around a pivotal decision at the end of the final boss. You HAVE to complete the platforming section I mentioned above to have access to that pivotal decision. There is a 4th bonus \"ending\" scene that requires a chain of NPC interactions through the game. I'm putting this here, so you don't sweat yourself too much worrying if you missed something or screwed something up. SLIGHT CRYPTIC SPOILER MESSAGE THAT WOULD HAVE HELPED ME AT THE END: [spoiler] When the wasp reigns in the brother, stay thy nail and peer into those radiant dreams that haunt him. [/spoiler]\n\nIf you consider yourself a fan of metroidvanias or souls-likes, you owe it to yourself to give this game a shot. That's really all I can say. The ratings tell the same story, but this is my personal invitation to you to try it. Even if you end up disliking it, it was worth finding out.", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1504619165, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_updated": 1504619165, "recommendationid": "34756834", "language": "english", "votes_down": 0, "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.505173", "voted_up": true}, {"author": {"last_played": 1505354624, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0, "num_reviews": 9, "playtime_forever": 2776, "steamid": "76561197995319188", "num_games_owned": 464}, "votes_funny": 0, "votes_up": 2, "comment_count": 0, "review": "M