comment_count": 0, "review": "[i](tl;dr) Hollow Knight is one of those games that are so remarkable and so pristine that they will be used as watermark all games in the same genre are going to be measured against. A stagerring achievement by just two people, it excels in all areas: the design is beautiful, the atmosphere gripping, the characters wonderfully written, the music evocative and the gameplay smooth, responsive and spiced with just the right amount of difficulty. All this combined with the fact that the developers are asking for much less than this game is worth makes Hollow Knight must for fans of the genre and curious gamers alike.[/i]\n\n[b]A Dream in Violet[/b]\n\nI will start this review with the most obviously praisworthy aspect of the game, that you'll notice right when you click that little play-button on your Steam-interface: while not being too technically impressive, the hand-drawn art is one of a kind. The areas all have a distinctly different, yet wonderful Gothic-atmosphere that conjures a world full of mystery, secrets, decay and yet - beauty. Special effects are used sparingly, which actually contributes to the full hand-drawn artstyle the developers were going for, and don't distract from the amazingly animated sprites and detailed backgrounds. The leitmotiv of the game is dreaming - and this games looks like a dream. It sounds like one as well; the score ranges from fail piano-melodies to impressive orchestral efforts, but always looms in the background, never taking away too much attention from the gameplay and art. \n\n[b]Smooth as Velvet[/b]\n\nWhereas immersive atmosphere, unique art and recognizable scores are certainly important for Metroidvanias, they are wasted on bad gameplay. Luckily, Hollow Knight excels also in this area; moving feels as smooth as in titles such as Symphony of the Night and much better than in - say - Super Metroid, and the jumping was even more precise than in the aforemented titles. In fact, the controls were so easily picked up and the feeling that my protagonist was doing exactly what I wanted without any delay was so present, that I will continue to measure every sidescroller against Hollow Knight in this regard. Over the course of the game, you will learn new abilities, for example the classic double-jump, that control just as good - nothing as nail-bitingly stupid such as Super Metroid's walljump.\n\nOnly the combat can take some time to get used to - after you hit something, you will experience a little backslash on your part, and if you are hit, the screen freezes for half a second. This contributes to the tactical nature of the game however, akin to Dark Souls - everything goes a little slower than in comparable games, tactical positioning and the enemies' movesets become more important because you can essentially stunlock nothing, while you cannot drown in a flurry of blows either. Every enemy has a pattern that wants to be learned, making the progression just as much a matter of the player's skill and experience than of his/her equipment. \n\n[b]Sadly Uniform[/b]\n\nThe only real gripe I have with the gameplay is how little you can customize your character. Granted, different charms change your character's abilites considerably, and the fact that you can only equip a limited amount of those power-ups gives you a lot think about, how you should approach one of the really difficult bossfights, or if you really need faster healing in a fast-paced platformer section. Still, you essentially have one weapon - your Nail, some kind of longsword - three different spells, three different special attacks and that's it. And the power-ups are not game-changing as well, just a little more reach, or easier money-collection or some temporary hitpoints. You get the idea. It's not a gamebreaker, by any means. Just something I've sadly missed over the course of my 50 hours in Hallownest.\n\n[b]A Loveletter to Immersion[/b]\n\nTo get the bad taste of petty nitpicking out of my mouth, I choose to continue this revew with the aspect that impressed me personally so much more than the near-perfect gameplay or the beautiful art: it's how much soul, how much passion was injected into this game. It truly is a consistent vision from beginning to end. To map the chart, you have to buy a map from a wanderer, which is crudely drawn and almost unusuable at first. Then, when you also pick up a quill, your character will start to scribble onto said map while being at a checkpoint, and update it with your latest findings. Many things, from small secrets, NPCs or upgrades up to entire, gigantic levels are just hidden away for people that explore the world really thoroughly. There is also a larger secret, aking to Castlevania's inverted castle, whose prequisites are not too esoteric, but highly missable for people that do not pay enough attention to the plot and the surroundings. \n\nDetails like that make Hallow Knight such a standout title. It is daring, yet every little detail is precicely thought out, taking one page or two from games such as Dark Souls or Deus Ex, titles that have one consistent vision which influenced every single decision in the process of making the game. Titles that do not define themselves not only as part of a distinct genre, but as an individual game with an individual soul and vision.", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1505698705, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_updated": 1505698858, "recommendationid": "35036733", "language": "english", "votes_down": 0, "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.502903", "voted_up": true}, {"author": {"last_played": 1506385577, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 208, "num_reviews": 1, "playtime_forever": 607, "steamid": "76561198165556546", "num_games_owned": 17}, "votes_funny": 0, "votes_up": 2, "comment_count": 0, "review": "Probably the best game of 2017. Everything in the game so far is perfect. There is so much content and they are still releasing dlc all 